# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2012-english-mayoral-referendums
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A post-legislative referendum was held in Scotland in 1979 to decide whether there was sufficient support among the Scottish electorate for a Scottish Assembly proposed in the Scotland Act 1978.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was an act to create a devolved deliberative assembly for Scotland.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A majority (51.6%) of voters supported the proposal, but an amendment to the Act stipulated that it would be repealed if less than 40% of the total electorate voted in favour.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] As there was a turnout of 64% the "Yes" vote represented only 32.9% of the registered electorate, and the act was subsequently repealed.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A second referendum to create a devolved legislature in Scotland was held in 1997 under a newly elected Labour government, which led to the enactment of the Scotland Act 1998 and the creation of a devolved Scottish Parliament in 1999.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The royal commission was intended to look at the constitutional structure of the United Kingdom and consider changes that should be made.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The commission examined various models of devolution, federalism and confederalism, on top of the break-up of the UK into separate sovereign states.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In relation to Scotland, eight of the commission's members supported a Scottish Assembly, via a devolved structure.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] It would recommend that the assembly would have around 100 members, elected under single transferable vote from multi-member constituencies.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The assembly would obtain powers in the areas of education, environment, health, home affairs, legal matters and social services, while agriculture, fisheries and food would be divided between the assembly and the UK government.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] After returning to power with a minority government in February 1974 election, Harold Wilson's Labour government published a white paper entitled *Democracy and Devolution: Proposals for Scotland and Wales*, published in September 1974.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The party gained a narrow majority of three seats in the election in October.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] By 1976, the Labour government, now led by James Callaghan, had lost its parliamentary majority entirely following a series of adverse by-election results.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The *Scotland and Wales Bill* was subsequently introduced in November 1976, but the government struggled to get the legislation through parliament.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Conservative opposition opposed its second reading, and on the first day of committee 350 amendments were put down.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In February 1977, the Bill's cabinet sponsor Michael Foot tabled a guillotine motion to attempt to halt the delays.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The motion was rejected and the government was forced to withdraw the Bill.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government returned to the issue of devolution in November 1977.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Separate bills for Scotland and Wales were published and support from the Liberals was obtained.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In spite of continued opposition requiring another guillotine motion, the Bills were passed.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] During the passage of the Scotland Act 1978 through Parliament, an amendment introduced by Labour MP George Cunningham added a requirement that the bill had to be approved by 40% of the total registered electorate, as well as a simple majority (50% + 1).
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The sample was made up of voters in Scotland and Wales.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Number of people who said they did not vote.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was a majority in favour of devolution.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A total of 1,230,937 (51.6%) voted at the referendum in favour of an Assembly, a majority of about 77,400 over those voting against.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, this total represented only 32.9% of the registered electorate as a whole.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Labour government held that the Act's requirements had not been met, and that devolution would therefore not be introduced for Scotland.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In the wake of the referendum the disappointed supporters of the bill conducted a protest campaign under the slogan "Scotland said 'yes'", officially launched in a Glasgow hotel on 7 March 1979.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In particular, the Scottish National Party (SNP) carried out a survey of the electoral register in the Edinburgh Central constituency.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This appeared to show that the register was so out of date that even in an area where major support for a "yes" vote might be expected, achievement of 40% of the electorate was virtually unattainable.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was because the majority of electors lived in older tenements or newer Council blocks of flats where flat numbers were not specified.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The work of electoral registration staff to obtain an accurate current register was almost impossible.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Under the terms of the Act, it could then be repealed by a Statutory instrument to be approved by Parliament.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government's decision to abandon devolution led the SNP to withdraw its support for the Labour government.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was in a minority in Parliament and had relied on deals with the smaller parties, including the SNP, for its survival.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] After establishing that the Liberals and the SNP would vote against the government in a confidence motion, the Conservative opposition tabled a motion on 28 March.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government was defeated by one vote, and a UK general election was subsequently called.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was won by the Conservatives, and Parliament voted to repeal the Act on 20 June 1979.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The **1979 Welsh devolution referendum** was a post-legislative referendum held on 1 March 1979 (Saint David's Day) to decide whether there was sufficient support for a Welsh Assembly among the Welsh electorate.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The referendum was held under the terms of the Wales Act 1978 drawn up to implement proposals made by the Kilbrandon Report published in 1973.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The plans were defeated by a majority of 4:1 (20.3% for and 79.7% against) with only 12% of the Welsh electorate voting in favour of establishing an assembly.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] A second referendum to create a devolved assembly for Wales was held in 1997, which led to the enactment of the Government of Wales Act 1998 and the creation of the National Assembly for Wales in 1999.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Both the Scotland Act and the Wales Act contained a requirement that at least 40% of all voters back the plan.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] It had been passed as an amendment by Islington South MP George Cunningham with the backing of Bedwellty MP Neil Kinnock.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Kinnock, the future leader of the Labour Party, called himself a "unionist".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] His stated view was that "between the mid-sixteenth century and the mid-eighteenth century Wales had practically no history at all, and even before that it was the history of rural brigands who have been ennobled by being called princes".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] He was one of six south Wales Labour MPs who opposed their own Government's plans, along with Leo Abse (Pontypool), Donald Anderson (Swansea East), Ioan Evans (Aberdare), Fred Evans (Caerphilly), and Ifor Davies (Gower).
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The government of James Callaghan did not have an overall majority in the House of Commons, and was therefore vulnerable to opposition from within its own ranks.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Labour party was split on home rule for Wales with a vocal minority opposed.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] They considered devolution as a danger to the unity of the UK and a concession to Welsh nationalism in the wake of by-election victories by Plaid Cymru.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Labour Party committed itself to devolution after coming to power in the February 1974 General Election.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] It followed the findings of a Royal Commission on the Constitution under Lord Kilbrandon.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Set up in 1969 in the wake of pressure to address growing support for independence in Scotland and Wales it delivered a split report in 1973.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Royal Commission recommended legislative and executive devolution to Scotland and Wales, with a minority supporting advisory Regional Councils for England.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] This plan was rejected as too bureaucratic and ill-advised in economic terms.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] New plans were brought forward by Harold Wilson's government in 1975 and 1976 which confined devolution to Scotland and Wales.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Scotland and Wales Bill had a difficult passage through Parliament and the government, lacking a majority to pass the plan, withdrew the legislation and introduced separate Bills for Scotland and Wales.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Hostile Labour MPs from the north of England, Wales and Scotland combined to insist that Assemblies could only be passed if directly endorsed by voters in a post-legislative referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] In 1978, John Morris, Baron Morris of Aberavon was under the impression that James Callaghan would call a general election in the autumn, but called it off.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] On 1 March, Saint David's Day, the devolution referendum was held but came at the end of the Winter of Discontent.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Factors such as "tribalism" divisions within Wales and impressions that a Welsh Assembly would be dominated by people of one particular region could have potentially caused the proposal to be rejected.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] According to John Morris, people in southern Wales were persuaded by the No campaign that the Assembly would be dominated by "bigoted Welsh-speakers from the north and the west" whilst in northern Wales, people had been convinced the Assembly would be a dominated Glamorgan County Council "Taffia".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] These factors led to a failed devolution referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Proposals for a more powerful Assembly in Scotland attracted the support of a majority of those who voted (1,230,937 for, 1,153,502 against) (see 1979 Scottish devolution referendum), but it amounted to just 32.5% of the total electorate, lower than the 40% threshold required.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The results sealed the fate of the minority Labour government, and as a direct result of the defeat of the referendums in Wales and Scotland the Scottish National Party (SNP) withdrew its support for the government, though Plaid Cymru supported the government in exchange for political concessions.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] In the House of Commons on 28 March 1979, the Labour government was defeated on a motion of no confidence by one vote, only the second time in the 20th century that a government was brought down in this way.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Labour's defeat in the 1979 General Election to Margaret Thatcher's Conservative Party precipitated a civil war within its own ranks, and the party was to be out of office for eighteen years.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The **Scottish devolution referendum of 1997** was a pre-legislative referendum held in Scotland on 11 September 1997 over whether there was support for the creation of a Scottish Parliament with devolved powers, and whether the Parliament should have tax-varying powers.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was "Yes–Yes": a majority voted in favour of both proposals, and the Parliament was established following an election in 1999.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The referendum was a Labour Party manifesto commitment and was held in their first term in office after the 1997 general election, under the provisions of the Referendums (Scotland and Wales) Act 1997.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was the second referendum held in Scotland over the question of devolution, the first being in 1979, and is to date the only major referendum to be held in any part of the United Kingdom where voters were asked two questions in the same plebiscite.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] A referendum was held in 1979 under a Labour government which stipulated that a Scottish Assembly would come into being if the referendum had been supported by 50% of votes cast plus a controversial rule whereby at least 40% of the electorate had to vote in favour.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Although 51.6% voted in favour, this was only 32.9% of the electorate so the Assembly was not brought into being.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Shortly afterwards, the predominantly anti-devolution-led Conservative Party won the 1979 general election.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] That government put devolution to one side but it was a policy area that remained on the agenda of the Labour Party.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] A Campaign for a Scottish Assembly was formed afterwards to continue the campaign.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] They brought together a committee of "prominent Scots" who drafted the document "A Claim of Right for Scotland".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The "Claim" was published in 1988 and signed by most Scottish politicians, local councils, trade unions and churches.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was agreed to form a Scottish Constitutional Convention, made up of existing MPs and councillors.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Labour Party included the establishment of a Scottish Parliament in its manifesto for the 1997 general election, which they won with a landslide majority of 179.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The electorate was asked to vote on two sets of statements which corresponded to both proposals.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Scottish Labour, the SNP, Scottish Liberal Democrats, and Scottish Greens campaigned for a "Yes" vote for both proposals whilst the Scottish Conservatives opposed both proposals.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Labour MP Tam Dalyell opposed the creation of the Parliament, but accepted that it should have tax-varying powers if it were to be established.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The official Yes campaign, *Scotland Forward* (styled "Scotland FORward"), was headed by the businessman Nigel Smith and came out of the groups that had previously formed the Scottish Constitutional Convention, along with the Scottish National Party.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was supported by the Labour, SNP, Liberal Democrat and Green parties.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The official No campaign, *Think Twice*, was headed by Brian Monteith, a former employee of the Conservative MP Michael Forsyth.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Board members included Donald Findlay, rector of the University of St Andrews and vice-chairman of Rangers F.C., and senior Conservative peer Lord Fraser.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, it struggled to get much business support as they were wary of opposing a project that had such support from the new government which had a large majority.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Campaigning in the referendum was suspended between the death and funeral of Diana, Princess of Wales.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was speculated that the Scottish referendum could have been postponed, but this would have required a recall of the UK Parliament and an amendment to the Referendums Act.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was "Yes-Yes": the majority voted "I agree" in favour of both proposals.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Two council areas had an overall "Yes-No" result – Dumfries and Galloway and Orkney.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] More votes were cast for the first question than the second in all regions (except Fife), with substantially more spoilt ballots for the second question, perhaps due to voter confusion over the two papers.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Votes in favour of tax-varying powers still commanded significant majority, when compared to establishing the Parliament per se.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] A majority voted 'I agree' in every local council, apart from in Dumfries & Galloway and Orkney.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] In response to the majority voting for "Yes" to both proposals, the UK Parliament passed the Scotland Act 1998.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] This established a Scottish Parliament for the first time since the adjournment of the pre-Union Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The devolved Parliament convened for the first time in May 1999, following its first election.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was a poll that the Conservative Party had to fight despite losing their "No" Campaign and having no Westminster seats in Scotland after losing the 1997 general election.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Scotland Act 1998 also created the Scottish Executive, later to become known as the Scottish Government.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Professor Tom Devine, academic at the University of Edinburgh, dubbed the referendum result "the most significant development in Scottish political history since the Union of 1707".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Prime Minister Tony Blair claimed that "the era of big centralised government is over".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The "Yes" campaign leaders Donald Dewar (Scottish Labour) and Alex Salmond (Scottish National Party) held different views over the devolution proposal.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, they put their political differences aside immediately after the vote in celebration.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Despite this, the SNP's calls for independence soon reignited with SNP leader Alex Salmond claiming that there would be an independent Scotland within his lifetime.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The "No" campaign did not share this optimism and feared that this vote was a catalyst towards the break-up of the Union.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Detail was also lacking in that the Scottish Constitutional Convention had failed to address issues such as the role of The Queen or aspects of tax-varying powers.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The **1997 Welsh devolution referendum** was a pre-legislative referendum held in Wales on 18 September 1997 over whether there was support for the creation of a National Assembly for Wales, and therefore a degree of self-government.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The referendum was a Labour manifesto commitment and was held in their first term after the 1997 election under the provisions of the Referendums (Scotland and Wales) Act 1997.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] This was the second referendum held in Wales over the question of devolution: the first referendum was held in 1979 and was defeated by a large majority.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The referendum resulted in a narrow majority in favour, which led to the passing of the Government of Wales Act 1998 and the formation of the National Assembly for Wales in 1999.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] A referendum was held in 1979 (with a parallel referendum in Scotland) proposing the creation of a Welsh Assembly, under James Callaghan's Labour government.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The referendum stipulated that a Welsh Assembly would be created if supported by 50% of votes cast and 40% of the total electorate.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Scottish referendum achieved the first condition but not the second, while the Welsh referendum was defeated by almost a 4:1 majority.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Indeed, although the Labour Party had committed itself to devolution in 1974 (following the advice of the Royal Commission on the Constitution) several Welsh Labour MPs (including Neil Kinnock) were very much opposed.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The 1979 referendum had been such a resounding defeat that it killed off any prospects of devolution in Wales for a generation.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The almost wholly anti-devolution, unionist Conservative Party won the 1979 general election (though Welsh Labour remained the largest party in Wales, the Conservatives only won 11 out of 36 seats in Wales) and remained in government until 1997.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Over this time, the Conservative Party became increasingly unpopular in Wales.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] A commitment to the creation of a Welsh Assembly with executive powers was again put into the Labour Party manifesto for the 1992 general election.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Labour Party shaped its policy of a Welsh Assembly under the guidance of Shadow Welsh Secretary Ron Davies and Welsh Office spokesmen Win Griffiths and Rhodri Morgan.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] In March 1996, Ron Davies signed an agreement with Alex Carlile, the Leader of the Welsh Liberal Democrats, which committed both parties to support a "Yes" vote in a Welsh devolution referendum in the event of a Labour victory at the 1997 general election.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The agreement was made in the context of a potential Lib-Lab pact should Labour not win an overall majority.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] There was no inter-party Constitutional Convention in Wales to define devolution as there had been in Scotland.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Labour's initial proposal to elect a Welsh Assembly using the traditional first-past-the-post system was reversed in late-1996 in favour of the Additional-member system.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] This change was vital in order to gain the support of Plaid Cymru and the Welsh Liberal Democrats in the event of a referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Unusually for a referendum just as in the 1997 Scottish devolution referendum the electorate was asked to vote on two statements rather than a question which corresponded to the following proposal.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The statements were issued both in English and Welsh.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The official Yes campaign, *Yes for Wales*, was supported by Labour, the Liberal Democrats and Plaid Cymru, though they also ran their own individual campaigns.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Labour anti-devolution MPs (including Llew Smith, among others) were subject to a tight parliamentary whip to ensure that the Labour Party was seen to be publicly behind the campaign.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] *Yes for Wales* placed a large emphasis on grassroots involvement in the campaign, with sectoral groups such as "Pensioners say Yes", and local branches throughout Wales.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The official No campaign, *Just Say NO*, was chaired by Nick Bourne, then-Conservative "Chief Spokesman in Wales".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The No campaign lacked the structure and finance of the Yes campaign, and suffered from the fact that the Conservatives' landslide defeat at the 1997 general election meant there were no Conservative MPs (and therefore no MPs supporting the No campaign) in Wales.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Additionally, the No campaign in 1997 did not have the support of local authorities; the fact that the Conservatives had reduced layers of local government from two to one in 1994 meant that this was not an issue as it had been in 1979.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Note: In Wales under the Welsh Language Act 1993 the Welsh language has equal status with the English language.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The overall result was declared in the Royal Welsh College of Music and Drama in Cardiff.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The proceeding officer was Professor Eric Sunderland.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The results of all 22 local authority areas were announced individually, and the result was close enough that everything in fact hung on the announcement from Carmarthenshire, which carried the Yes vote.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The difference between the 'agree' and 'disagree' vote was 6,721.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The **1998 Greater London Authority referendum** was held in Greater London on 7 May 1998.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The referendum asked whether there was support for creating a Greater London Authority composed of a directly elected Mayor of London and a London Assembly to scrutinise the Mayor's actions.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The referendum was held under the Greater London Authority (Referendum) Act 1998 provisions.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] Polling day coincided with the 1998 London local elections.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] Labour's 1997 general election manifesto, *New Labour, New Life for Britain,* mentioned establishing a directly elected mayor and authority.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] This would be the first London-wide government since the abolition of the Greater London Council.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The government published a green paper with the title *New Leadership for London* in July 1997.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] This laid out the principles of the GLA: a strong mayor and a "strategic" assembly.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The full proposals were confirmed in a March 1998 white paper entitled *A* *Mayor and Assembly for London* which set out the full details of the proposal.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] Voters were permitted to select either a simple **YES** or **NO** answer.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The 'Yes' vote won in every London Borough, though support was generally larger in Inner London than in Outer London.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The lowest support figures were 60.5% in Havering and 57.1% in Bromley; the greatest were 83.8% in Haringey and 81.8% in Lambeth.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The income level of boroughs was an even greater factor affecting the outcome.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The government passed the Greater London Authority Act 1999, creating the Greater London Authority.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The first elections for the Mayor of London and the London Assembly were held in May 2000.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The Conservatives criticised the referendum's low turnout, and suggested that it undermined the legitimacy of the referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The Labour Party refuted this suggestion, by instead suggesting that many people had decided to not vote because they perceived the result as a foregone conclusion, and that there was significant enthusiasm for a "strong, independent, political voice that can speak up for Londoners".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The establishment of directly elected mayors was suggested as possibly as constitutionally significant as Scottish devolution or Welsh devolution.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] A referendum was held in Northern Ireland on 22 May 1998 over whether there was support for the Good Friday Agreement.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The result was a majority (71.1%) in favour.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] A simultaneous referendum held in the Republic of Ireland produced an even larger majority (94.4%) in favour.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The total number of people who voted in both referendums was 2,499,078.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] All the main UK political parties (Labour, Conservative, and Liberal Democrat) supported the Yes campaign.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The only two parties in the Forum to campaign against the Agreement were the Democratic Unionist Party and the UK Unionist Party, though many prominent individuals in the Ulster Unionists also did so.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] Some minor parties campaigned against it.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] Republican Sinn Féin, which at the time did not run candidates in Northern Ireland, still opposes the agreement.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] In the Republic of Ireland, all parties represented in the Oireachtas were in favour – Fianna Fáil, Fine Gael, Labour, Progressive Democrats, Democratic Left, Green Party, Sinn Féin and the Socialist Party.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The referendum saw a large majority 'Yes' vote across the province on Friday 22 May 1998.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] Turnout, at 81.1%, was very high for a developed country where voting is not compulsory.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] Turnout in the equivalent referendum in the Republic of Ireland was average for a constitutional referendum but returned almost universal approval (94.39%).
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The referendum in the Republic of Ireland was held on the same day but rather than explicitly seeking approval of the Agreement itself it sought endorsement of constitutional amendments required by the Agreement, and produced an overwhelming Yes vote in favour.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The turnout in Northern Ireland was noticeably high at 81.1% and also quite high evenly throughout Northern Ireland, compared to many elections where turnout is highest in strong nationalist areas and significantly lower in unionist areas.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] It is estimated that approximately 147,000 people who do not normally vote in elections turned out to vote in the referendum, most of them in traditionally staunch unionist areas.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] In the Republic the turnout was lower, at 56.3%.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The UK Parliament passed the Northern Ireland Act 1998, while in the Republic the Nineteenth Amendment of the Constitution Act 1998 passed into law.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The **Mayor of Mansfield** is the directly elected executive mayor of the district of Mansfield in Nottinghamshire, England.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] A new appointment was created from 2002 following moves made by a Mansfield-based businessman to change the governance of Mansfield after a public referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] Andy Abrahams was elected on 3 May 2019 by two votes from sitting incumbent Kate Allsop after two recounts of the second-preference votes.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The incumbent from 2002 to May 2015 was Tony Egginton, succeeded by his fellow Mansfield Independent Forum party member Kate Allsop, who stood against Egginton in 2002 as a Conservative.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The role of elected mayor was created following a public referendum on 2 May 2002.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The referendum was the culmination of a campaign led by local businessman Stewart Rickersey to have a directly elected mayor for the district.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The inaugural election was scheduled for 17 October 2002.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] Prior to the referendum Mansfield District Council was governed by a leader and cabinet system, in which a leader of the council was elected indirectly from the largest group elected to the council.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] Labour councillor Jim Hawkins had been leader of the council from its creation in 1974; he did not stand for election as mayor, with Labour's candidate being the deputy leader of the council, Lorna Carter.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] Tony Egginton was Mayor of Mansfield from October 2002 until retirement in May 2015, being replaced at scheduled elections by a fellow candidate for the Mansfield Independent Forum political party, Kate Allsop.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] Much was said of the first Executive Mayor, but during his time in office, Mansfield struggled with local land development and many projects across the region faltered.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] Egginton (in office 2002–2015) was criticised by some councillors and residents for placing too much focus on self-publicity, as opposed to publicity for the town.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The issue was raised again after his prominent role in the homecoming ceremony for swimmer Rebecca Adlington after her Gold Medal successes at the 2008 Beijing Olympic Games.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The 2011 election was third direct election for the mayoralty of Mansfield.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The sitting mayor, Tony Egginton, successfully defended his position, which he first won in 2002.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] On 5 May 2011 he was elected for the third time, winning in the second round of voting with the narrow majority of 67 over the Labour candidate Stephen Yemm.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The 2015 election was fourth direct election for the mayoralty of Mansfield.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The sitting mayor, Tony Egginton, had previously announced his intention to retire.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] On 7 May 2015 the candidates were former Labour-member turned Independent Phil Shields, Labour's Martin Lee and Mansfield Independent Forum's Kate Allsop, who after the second round of voting won from Martin Lee with a considerable majority.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The 2019 election took place on 2 May 2019.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The candidates were Incumbent Mayor Kate Allsop from the Mansfield Independent Forum (MIF), Conservative perennial candidate George Jabbour, and District and County Councillor Steve Garner, formerly with MIF, standing as an independent.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] In late March Mansfield Labour group selected a third candidate in former teacher and civil engineer Andy Abrahams, following the suspension of Cllr Sean McCallum and resignation of Paul Bradshaw.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] In March 2019, 2015 Mayoral Candidate and former District Councillor Philip Shields announced his intention to run in 2019.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The 2023 mayoral election took place on 4 May 2023.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] Final candidates declared in early April were Andy Abrahams (Labour), Mick Barton (Mansfield Independents), Andre Camilleri (Conservative), Karen Seymour (Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition) and Julie Margaret Tasker-Love-Birks (Independent).
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] Both the Conservative and Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition candidates' campaigns included potentially seeking to abolish the position of executive mayor, subject to a successful public referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] Labour's Andy Abrahams was re-elected with a significant margin of over 4,000 votes, in contrast with his previous win by two votes.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2002-mansfield-mayoral-election] The voting system was first past the post – changing from the supplementary vote system used previously.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] A series of **mayoral referendums** were held on 3 May 2012 in England's 11 largest cities to determine whether to introduce directly elected mayors to provide political leadership, replacing their current council leaders, who are elected by the local council.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Parliamentary approval was granted for referendums to be held in Birmingham, Bradford, Bristol, Coventry, Leeds, Manchester, Newcastle upon Tyne, Nottingham, Sheffield and Wakefield.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The government had also intended to hold referendums on whether to introduce directly elected mayors in Leicester and Liverpool, however before the government could order these referendums, the two city councils had already decided to adopt a mayoral system themselves.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Leicester City Council voted to introduce a mayor in 2010 without holding a referendum, and an election was held in 2011 for the position.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Meanwhile, despite legislation being passed for a referendum in Liverpool, the City Council voted to bypass the referendum and to instead hold a mayoral election on the same day as other local elections in May.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] In addition, Doncaster Borough Council decided to hold a referendum on the same day, to determine whether to retain their elected mayoral system, having been one of the earliest authorities to adopt one, in 2001.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] On 26 January 2012 electors in Salford voted in favour of an elected mayor by 17,344 votes to 13,653.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] There was an inaugural 2012 Salford mayoral election on the same day as 2012 United Kingdom local elections.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Directly elected mayorship in the United Kingdom was first established by Tony Blair's Labour Government with the creation of the Mayor of London.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The Local Government Act 2000 then provided all councils in England and Wales with a range of options as to how to operate its executive functions, including the option of a directly elected mayor.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The Act also provided that a petition of more than 5% of the electorate of a council area could force that council to hold a referendum on whether to introduce a directly elected mayor.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] As of January 2011, there had been 40 of these referendums with a further one planned in Salford for 26 January 2012.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Of these 40, only 13 had voted in favour of the introduction of a mayor, with 27 rejecting the proposal.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] These figures included two referendums held in Stoke-on-Trent, the first in 2002 that had approved the creation of a directly elected mayor, and the second in 2008 that had seen the electorate vote to abolish the position.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] In 2009, the then Conservative Opposition, who were well ahead in opinion polling for the following year's general election, had said they would introduce elected mayors for England's 12 biggest cities, if they won power.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] In the 2010 general election, they did win power, albeit in a coalition government with the Liberal Democrats, and Prime Minister David Cameron reaffirmed his previous commitment to hold a series of referendums on whether to introduce mayors for the biggest English cities.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The Department for Communities and Local Government launched a consultation on 1 November 2011 to decide what powers any newly created city mayors could have at their disposal.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The list of powers the government considered devolving included power over rail and bus services, skills, apprenticeships, and money to invest in high speed broadband and other economic infrastructure.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Shortly after announcing this consultation, the government confirmed that 11 referendums would all be held on 3 May 2012.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The referendum was held prior to decisions on the Mayoral responsibilities.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Amongst those campaigning for a 'yes' vote in Birmingham were Gisela Stuart, Labour MP for Birmingham Edgbaston, Liam Byrne, Labour MP for Birmingham Hodge Hill, Sir Albert Bore, the leader of the Labour group on Birmingham City Council, and Siôn Simon, the former Labour MP for Birmingham Erdington.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Liam Byrne confirmed he would stand for his party's nomination were voters to approve plans in the referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] He was supported by ex-Birmingham City Council leader Sir Albert Bore.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Those advocating a 'no' vote included Roger Godsiff, Labour MP for Birmingham Hall Green and John Hemming, Liberal Democrat MP for Birmingham Yardley.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The post of West Midlands Mayor, chairing the West Midlands Combined Authority, was introduced in 2017 without a further referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] George Galloway, who was elected MP for Bradford West in a by-election five weeks before the referendum, declared his support for a directly elected mayor shortly after his election, making him the sole Bradford MP in favour of the proposal.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The out-going Leader of Bristol City Council, Barbara Janke, was opposed to the introduction of a directly elected mayor, as was the rest of her Liberal Democrat group, whilst the city's Green Party were also opposed.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The Conservatives were the only party in the city to openly support the introduction of a mayor, whilst Labour adopted a neutral approach of "let the people decide".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The leader of Bristol City Council described the electorate as "palpably apathetic" on the issue.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Labour controlled Coventry Council said they believed an elected mayor is unnecessary, and were supported by the Liberal Democrats, Socialist, and the majority of Conservative councillors in a council motion formally opposing the idea of a directly elected mayor.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] All of Coventry's MPs declared their opposition to the plan too, with the sole exception of Bob Ainsworth, former Defence Secretary and MP for Coventry North East, who suggested that the position would make the council more accountable to the electorate.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The post of West Midlands Mayor (covering the West Midlands county, including Coventry) was introduced in 2017, without a further referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The Labour leader of Leeds City Council criticised the proposals for an elected mayor as "utter madness", whilst the Conservative and Liberal Democrat group leaders on the City Council also both expressed their opposition to the plan, and advocated a 'no' vote.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The non-political Chief Executive of Manchester City Council, Sir Howard Bernstein, responded to the government's consultation of elected mayors by stating that such a position was not suitable for Manchester.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Some analysts and local business leaders have stated their opposition to a mayoral system of local governance in Manchester and have stated the progress Manchester has made over the past 20 years that shows the current system is adequate.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Amongst the local political parties, the leader of the Liberal Democrat group on Manchester City Council publicly declared his support for the proposals, whilst the *Manchester Evening News* reported that many Labour politicians were "quietly opposed to change".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Manchester narrowly voted against a mayor; the result was however much closer than many local politicians and media predicted, and far closer than the other ten cities which also held mayoral referendums.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] A poll of almost 1000 Mancunians by the MEN in April 2012 found a majority preferred the current system of a council leader and their cabinet rather than a mayoral system of local government.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The poll found however that a majority would favour a mayor for the wider Greater Manchester region, which includes 10 metropolitan boroughs, over a system of individual mayors for towns and cities.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] On 3 November 2014 it was announced that a directly elected Mayor for the Greater Manchester region would be introduced with the first Mayoral elections to be held in 2017.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] A campaign group advocating a 'yes' vote in the Newcastle referendum was led by Brian Moore, former Chairman of the Newcastle Conservative Party.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The idea was backed by Newcastle First, a local political party, and the Conservative Member of Parliament for Hexham.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The local Labour and Liberal Democrat groups had previously expressed their opposition to an elected mayor but both of their group leaders declared their intentions to stand if the position was created.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The local Liberal Democrats also expressed their opposition to the proposals, and advocated a 'no' vote.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The Labour and Liberal Democrat groups on Sheffield City Council both expressed opposition to the idea of an elected mayor, whilst the regional director of the Confederation of British Industry, Andrew Palmer, also expressed doubt over the plan.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] The trade union Unison also actively campaigned for a 'no' vote in the referendum.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Support for the proposal was given by the local Conservative party, who claimed a directly elected mayor would be more accountable to the electorate, as well as other local business owners who claimed a directly elected mayor would hold a "stronger mandate to take decisions".
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Although critical of the post, Wakefield Council leader Peter Box suggested he would put his name forward if the referendum was passed.
[src:2012-english-mayoral-referendums/2012-english-mayoral-referendums] Amongst the local political parties, the Conservative group leader on Wakefield Council declared his party's support for the status quo, whilst the local UK Independence Party expressed support for the mayoral position.
